 It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda was born in 1135, in Meißen, Kreis Meißen, Saxony, Germany as the daughter of Goswin von Heinsberg III. She married Count Robert Hervey. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 20 January 1189, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1135–20 January 1189":"1135–20. jaanuar 1189","1135–1189":"1135–1189","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1189":"1189","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","20 January 1189":"20. jaanuar 1189","1170":"1170","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England":"England","Meißen, Meißen, Dresden, Germany":"Meißen, Kreis Meißen, Sachsen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1135–20 January 1189":"1135–20. tammikuuta 1189","1135–1189":"1135–1189","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","about